\p{[Lurie](lurie-htt) states the following result as Proposition 7.2.1.14 of [Higher Topos Theory](lurie-htt):}

\blockquote{
  Let \XTop be an âˆž-topos and let \Mor{\tau_{\leq 0}}{\XTop}{\tau_{\leq 0}\XTop} be the left adjoint to the inclusion. A morphism \Mor{\phi}{U}{X} in \XTop is an effective epimorphism if and only if in #{\tau_{\leq 0}\prn{\phi}} is an effective epimorphism in the ordinary topos #{\HtpyCat\prn{\tau_{\leq0}\XTop}}.
}

\p{[Several users of MathOverflow have noticed](https://mathoverflow.net/questions/452920/effective-epimorphisms-and-0-truncations-htt-7-2-1-14) that the proof of this result given by [Lurie](lurie-htt) is circular. The result is true and can be recovered in a variety of ways, as pointed out in the [MathOverflow discussion](https://mathoverflow.net/questions/452920/effective-epimorphisms-and-0-truncations-htt-7-2-1-14). For expository purposes, I would like to show how to prove this result directly in univalent foundations using standard results about #{n}-truncations from the [HoTT Book](hottbook).}

